e, France":"Broyes, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France","France":"France","Baye, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Baye, Marne, Grand Est, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Broyes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Breyhel</b>, a variant of <b>Breil</b>, itself a variant of <b>Brühl</b> (see   Bruehl  ). The surname <i>Breyhel</i> is no longer found in Germany. Compare   Briles  .","History: Johannes Breyhel and his family, from Oetisheim in Württemberg, were among a group of German colonists sponsored by VA Governor Alexander Spotswood in 1714. They founded a settlement called Germanna in Orange County. Hans Jacob Breyhel (born 1705) was the ancestor of the Broyles family, while his brother Conrad was founder of the Briles family."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruehl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Armin, Dieter, Frieda, Horst, Lothar.","German (<b>Brühl</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a swampy area, Middle High German <i>brüel</i>, Middle Low German <i>brūl</i> ‘swampy land with brushwood’.","German and Jewish (western Ashkenazic) (<b>Brühl</b>): habitational name from Brühl in Germany. Compare   Bruhl  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon De Broyes II was born in 1136, in France, his father, Simon Seigneur de Broyes I, was 42 and his mother, Felicity Brienne, was 32. He married Agnes de Joigny in 1175. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1188, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1136–1188":"1136–1188","1120–1199":"1120–1199","1124–1136":"1124–1136","1157–1209":"1157–1209","1176–1243":"1176–1243","1095–1140":"1095–1140","1104–1178":"1104–1178","Aft 21 June 1178":"pärast 21. juunit 1178","1176":"1176","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","4 January 1140":"4. jaanuar 1140","1104":"1104","1136":"1136","1157":"1157","1124":"1124","1178":"1178","1188":"1188","1243":"1243","1199":"1199","about 1125":"umbes 1125","1209":"1209","Broyes, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Broyes, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Baye, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Baye, Marne, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1136–1188":"1136–1188","1120–1199":"1120–1199","1124–1136":"1124–1136","1157–1209":"1157–1209","1176–1243":"1176–1243","1095–1140":"1095–1140","1104–1178":"1104–1178","Aft 21 June 1178":"21. kesäkuuta 1178 jälkeen","1176":"1176","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","4 January 